### **1\. Configure Layer 3 Information in All Routers**

#### **Router R1**

config terminal  
interface f0/0  
ip address 10.10.12.2 255.255.255.0  
no shutdown  
exit

no shutdown

**2\. Configure RIP v2 in Routers Under RIP Domain**

#### **Router R1**

enable  
config terminal  
router rip  
version 2  
network 10.10.12.0  
exit  
![][image9]

####  

#### **Router R2**

| enable config terminal router rip version 2 network 10.10.12.0 network 10.10.23.0 exit | ![][image10] |
| :---- | :---- |

#### **Router R3**

| enable config terminal router rip version 2 network 10.10.23.0 exit | ![][image11] |
| :---- | :---- |

### **3\. Configure EIGRP in Routers Under EIGRP Domain**

#### **Router R3**

enable  
config terminal  
router eigrp 1  
network 10.10.34.0  
network 10.10.45.0  
exit  
![][image12]

#### **Router R4**

enable  
config terminal  
router eigrp 1  
network 10.10.34.0  
network 10.10.46.0  
exit  
![][image13]

####  **Router R5**

| enable config terminal router eigrp 1 network 10.10.45.0 network 10.10.56.0 exit | ![][image14] |
| :---- | :---- |

#### **Router R6**

enable  
config terminal  
router eigrp 1  
network 10.10.46.0  
network 10.10.56.0  
exit  
![][image15]

### **4\. Distribute RIP Routing Table into EIGRP Domain and Vice-Versa**

enable  
config terminal  
router eigrp 1  
redistribute rip metric 10000 100 255 1 1500  
exit

router rip  
redistribute eigrp 1 metric 1  
exit

### **6\. Active Path from R6 to R1**

To find the active path, use the `trace` command on Router R1:  
Trace 10.10.46.2 (Router 6\)  
Trace 10.10.56.1 (Router 6\)

![][image19]

### **Analysis:**

The traceroute to 10.10.56.1 shows lower round-trip times (RTT) compared to the traceroute to 10.10.46.2. This indicates that the path through **10.10.56.1** is likely the actively used path.

R1 \-\> R2 \-\> R3 \-\> R5 \-\> R6
